An encoder motor is basically a normal DC motor + a sensor (encoder) that tells you how fast and how much the motor has rotated.
What is an Encoder Motor?

It combines:

A DC motor → makes the wheel spin
An encoder → measures rotation

So instead of just “moving”, you now know:

✔ Speed
✔ Direction
✔ Distance traveled
⚙️ Main Idea (Simple)
Motor spins → Encoder senses rotation → Sends signals to Arduino
What is the Encoder?

Inside the motor, there is:

A rotating disk (with slots or magnets)
A sensor (optical or magnetic)
Every time the motor rotates, the encoder generates pulses (signals).

Types of Encoder Signals

Most encoder motors give 2 signals:

Channel A & Channel B

These are:

Square wave signals
Slightly shifted from each other
This helps detect:

Speed
Direction
How it works (step-by-step)
Motor rotates
Encoder disk spins
Sensor detects movement
Sends pulses to Arduino
Arduino counts pulses
